## G21 Hierarchical Goals View
**Status:** implemented
**Tags:** stack:frontend, module:specs
**Depends on:** G7

1. **One-Level Goal Hierarchy**
   - Goals can have parent-child relationships (one level deep only)
   - Each parent goal can have multiple subgoals
   - Each subgoal has exactly one parent (or is top-level)
   - Subgoals detected automatically via dotted ID notation (e.g., `G9.1` is child of `G9`, `G9.1.2` is invalid)
   - Data model: `parent_id` field derived from ID parsing (not manually set)

2. **Tree Visualization**
   - Tree view is the default (and only) view mode
   - **All branches collapsed by default** - only top-level goals visible on initial load
   - Visual hierarchy with indentation; root goals and sub-goals have distinct styling
   - Rendered as `<div>`-based tree nodes (replaced earlier `<table>`-based layout)
   - Show goal metadata (ID, priority, status, tags) in tree nodes
   - Expand/collapse state is client-side only (session-scoped)

3. **Toggle Area Interaction**
   - Fixed-width 2.5rem toggle area on the left of each root goal
   - Children count badge + expand chevron combined into a single clickable span
   - **Goals WITH sub-goals**: toggle area visible; clicking expands/collapses; hover shows "N sub-goals"
   - **Goals WITHOUT sub-goals**: toggle area removed entirely; the whole row click opens the detail modal
   - Sub-goals (level > 0) render with left indent but no toggle area

4. **Goal Detail Modal**
   - Centered modal with backdrop blur; opened by clicking any tree row
   - Header: ID badge + title + close button
   - Meta bar: priority pill, status badge, tags (shortened, color-coded)
   - Body: RelationsPanel (parents/children) + description content
   - Inline edit mode: switches to GoalEditor within the same modal
   - ESC key or click-outside closes; click on card content prevents close

5. **Typed Tag System**
   - Tags use `kind:value` format (e.g., `stack:frontend`, `module:specs`)
   - Multiple tags per spec item; all 7 categories tagged (Goals, Architecture, Designs, Plans, Tests, Reviews, Reports)
   - Tag display in tree rows: shortened form (`stack:frontend` → `frontend`), color-coded by type
   - `stack:*` = blue, `module:*` = purple; hover shows full tag text
   - Sidebar filtering: Stack and Module drawers with multi-select pill filters; AND logic across filter types

6. **Sidebar Filtering (SpecsView)**
   - Three `<details>` drawer sections in sidebar: Category, Stack, Module
   - Category drawer switches active section (Goals, Architecture, Designs, etc.)
   - Stack and Module drawers show tag pills; multi-select with active state
   - Filtered items use AND logic: item must match at least one selected stack AND at least one selected module
   - Default expanded state for all drawers

| Decision | Choice |
|----------|--------|
| Hierarchy Depth | One level (parent → subgoals only) |
| Subgoal Detection | Dotted ID notation (e.g., `G9.1` is child of `G9`) |
| Classification System | Typed tags (`kind:value`) — `stack` and `module` kinds |
| Default View State | All branches collapsed |
| View Modes | Tree view only (no flat toggle) |
| Toggle Area | Fixed 2.5rem; removed entirely for leaf goals |
| Detail Interaction | Modal (not inline expansion) |

- Tree view renders efficiently for 100+ goals
- Expand/collapse operations complete in <100ms
- Existing subgoals automatically detected via ID parsing
- Tags display correctly as shortened color-coded badges on tree nodes
- Sidebar filtering works across all categories with Stack/Module drawers
- All branches collapsed on initial load

## G22 Errand Agent Dispatch enables any profession to offload research tasks without context pollution
**Status:** implemented
**Tags:** stack:backend, module:errand
**Depends on:** G1, G17, G13

- [x] `dispatch` tool available to all relay professions for firing lightweight side-tasks
- [x] `gofer` profession defined with minimal soul, cheap model tier, and short turn limit
- [x] Errand runs in isolated message context — master's chat history stays clean
- [x] Only final summary/fact returns to caller; intermediate tool outputs remain in errand log
- [x] Full errand chat log persisted and visible in same session view for boss audit
- [x] Errand agents do NOT participate in relay pipeline — no `handoff_to`, no approval gates
- [x] Gofer uses cheapest configured model tier (e.g., Claude Haiku or GPT-4o-mini)

1. **Dispatch Tool Interface**
   - Any profession calls `dispatch` with: `agent` (profession_id, default "gofer"), `task` (string), `context` (optional caller context)
   - Backend validates target is in `dispatchable_to` list (not `handoff_to`)
   - Tool returns after errand completes or hits max_turns

2. **Gofer Profession Definition**
   - Profession id: `gofer`, display name: "Gofer", persona: "Gus"
   - Phase: `ForgePhase::Errand` (new phase, lower than Intake)
   - Tools: `shell`, `read_file`, `search`, `list_specs`, `read_specs`, `query_wiki`
   - No `handoff_to`, no `approval_gates`, `max_turns: 20`, `token_budget: 4_000`
   - Model tier: `Light` (cheapest available provider)

3. **Isolated Errand Context**
   - Each dispatch spawns a new `ErrandSession` with its own `message_history` Vec
   - Errand session linked to parent session via `parent_session_id`
   - System prompt = gofer soul + task description + caller context
   - Errand runs standard ReAct loop but writes to isolated message list

4. **Result Compression**
   - Final assistant message from errand is returned as the `dispatch` tool result string
   - Optional: errand can be instructed to return structured JSON (list of files, key findings)
   - Master's chat history only grows by the dispatch tool call + result (~200-400 tokens)

5. **Audit Trail & Visibility**
   - Full errand message history persisted to `errands/` subdirectory in session store
   - Frontend renders errand as a collapsible thread nested under caller's message
   - Boss can expand to see all tool calls, reasoning, and intermediate outputs
   - Errand thread shows token cost separately from master session cost

| Decision | Choice |
|----------|--------|
| Dispatch mechanism | Tool-based (`dispatch` tool) not `bring_in` |
| Context isolation | Separate `ErrandSession` message list, not shared history |
| Model selection | Cheapest configured tier (Light) — configurable per API source |
| Errand visibility | Collapsible nested thread in same chat view |
| Persistence | JSON files in `errands/` subdir, not SQLite |
| Max turns | 20 (hard cap to prevent runaway) |
| Return format | Plain text summary (default), optional structured JSON |

- Architect can dispatch "find how auth works" and receive 200-token summary instead of 5k-token grep output
- Master's chat history does not contain errand tool outputs
- Errand thread visible and expandable in frontend
- Gofer runs on cheapest model, saving ~80% on errand token cost vs master model
- Errand completes within 20 turns or returns truncated result

## G23 Automatic Relay Mode
**Status:** implemented
**Tags:** stack:backend, module:relay
**Depends on:** G6, G16

1. **Chat-to-Relay Bridge**
   - Chat agents (Advisor, Assistant, Architect) can call `spawn_relay` tool to launch an autonomous background relay pipeline
   - Tool accepts `flow_id` (standard, post_discovery, fast_track, bug_fix), `task`, `mode` (gsd/check), optional `context`
   - Tool validates that caller's profession has `spawn_relay` in `allowed_tools`
   - Tool returns `run_id`, `monitor_url`, and confirmation JSON

2. **Background Auto-Driver**
   - New `relay/driver.rs` module drives relay runs to completion in background tokio tasks
   - Loop: `advance_run` → `AgentTurn::run()` → `submit_handoff` → repeat
   - At `WaitForHuman` gates: driver polls every 2s until gate is resolved via RelayView
   - Driver sets `CURRENT_PROJECT` thread-local so specs tools work in relay context
   - Driver constructs step messages from: initial task + previous handoff + gate feedback

3. **New Flow: Post-Discovery**
   - Skips `intake` and `discover` steps since chat already completed discovery
   - Pipeline: architect → planner → tester → coder → tester → reviewer → documenter
   - Loop back from `run-tests` to `code` on failure (max 3 iterations)

4. **Chat Integration**
   - Forge stream handler intercepts `spawn_relay` tool results
   - Creates `RunEntry` in `RunStore`, spawns background driver
   - Emits `RelaySpawned` SSE event to chat frontend
   - Replaces raw tool JSON with friendly message: "Relay pipeline started: {run_id}"

5. **Frontend Relay Cards**
   - New `RelaySpawned`, `RelayUpdate`, `RelayGateWaiting`, `RelayComplete` SSE events
   - Chat header shows "Relay" button when active relay runs exist
   - Inline relay cards show: flow name, status badge, "Monitor →" link to RelayView
   - Relay view auto-refreshes on run events

6. **Token Tracking in Relay Turns**
   - `ToolChatEvent::Usage` wired into `TurnResult::tokens_used`
   - `AgentTurn::to_handoff()` uses real token counts instead of estimates
   - Tool guard added to `AgentTurn::run()` to block tools not in profession's `allowed_tools`

| Decision | Choice |
|----------|--------|
| Trigger mechanism | Tool-based (`spawn_relay`) not system watcher |
| Driver concurrency | One background task per relay run |
| Gate polling | 2-second sleep loop (simple, no extra channels) |
| Context passing | Initial task string + previous HandoffDocument::render() |
| Profession allowlist | assistant, advisor, architect can spawn relays |

- Advisor soul updated to teach Isaac when to call `spawn_relay` vs `bring_in`
- `post_discovery` flow added to built-in flows alongside `standard`, `fast_track`, `bug_fix`
- Relay API exposes `run_store()` and `event_sender()` for forge module access

